INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(187, 8, '2015-05-23 17:04:42', '2015-05-23 11:34:42', 'A drug addict, A Zen disciple, a selfish individual, a loyal friend, the worst boss and the CEO of the world’s most valuable company.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/unnamed.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-188" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/unnamed-300x225.jpg" alt="unnamed" width="300" height="225" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThis is what Steve Jobs was like, a mirror. A mirror to himself in that, he was the exact opposite of what he was and a mirror to others in that, they could see the faults in themselves when Jobs was around.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHis saga is the entrepreneurial myth written large. He cofounded Apple in his Parent’s garage with Steve Wozniak, was ousted a decade later and then returned, twelve years later to rescue Apple Inc. from the brink of bankruptcy and in 2011, helped Apple become the world’s most valuable company. In this process, he helped transform seven major industries; Personal Computing, animated movies, digital music, smartphones, tablet computing, retail stores and digital publishing.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="line-height: 1.5;"><a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/618w_steve_jobs_memorial_gallery_2.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-191" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/618w_steve_jobs_memorial_gallery_2-300x183.jpg" alt="618w_steve_jobs_memorial_gallery_2" width="300" height="183" /></a></span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<span style="line-height: 1.5;">And yet, his life was so much more than this.</span>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHis life was always about living it in binary terms. A product was insanely great or a piece of crap, a dish served to him was the best thing ever or downright inedible. And similarly, the highs of his life were unimaginable but the lows were rock bottom and terrifying. But there was only one singularity to his life, he loved what he did. And in his commencement address at Stanford in 2005, that was what he asked of the graduating students, to keep looking for what they love, to not settle for anything less.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n“The only way to do great work is to love what you do. Keep looking, Don’t Settle. As with all matters of the heart, you’ll know when you find it. And, like any great relationship, it just gets better and better as the years roll on, So keep looking until you find it, Don’t settle.”\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/alg-steve-jobs-stanford-jpg.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-192" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/alg-steve-jobs-stanford-jpg-300x200.jpg" alt="alg-steve-jobs-stanford-jpg" width="300" height="200" /></a>\r\n\r\nHe was a perfection Nazi, one obsessed with perfecting each bit of the each work he ever did. During the development of almost every product he ever created, Jobs hit the pause button and went back to the drawing board because he felt it wasn’t perfect.  His perfectionism extended even to parts unseen. As a young boy, he had helped his father build a fence around their backyard, and he was told they had to use as much care on the back of the fence as on the front. “Nobody will ever know,” Steve said. His father replied “But you will know.”\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/ipadiphoneipod.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-193" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/ipadiphoneipod-300x250.jpg" alt="ipadiphoneipod" width="300" height="250" /></a>\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nHe took his father’s lessons to heart and today, as a person who read a 560 page biography of him, there are many lessons I’ve learnt.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nThe book by Walter Isaacson is only a vast collection of anecdotes, incidents and happenings that shaped his life but for me, it is a Bible, having an answer to each question of mine.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/FB_IMG_1430991572257.jpg"><img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-189" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/05/FB_IMG_1430991572257-300x294.jpg" alt="FB_IMG_1430991572257" width="300" height="294" /></a>\r\n\r\nI believe that every great act in Human History can trace its roots back to the right person picking up the right book.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nI know that I’ve picked up the right book, I just need to become the right person', 'A Tale of Processors and Poetry', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'a-tale-of-processors-and-poetry', '', '', '2015-05-23 17:04:42', '2015-05-23 11:34:42', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=187', 0, 'post', '', 0);
