INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(229, 1, '2015-06-10 20:21:39', '2015-06-10 14:51:39', '<em>''Th</em><em>at night I realized what all authors and writers go through. The moment I  penned the last word of my story, I felt satisfied knowing that I had done justice to the characters of my story. It was a beautiful feeling. But then, my heart broke knowing that I had to bid goodbye to them.Though it wasn''t really a goodbye.''</em>\r\n\r\nHonestly, I wasn''t intending on writing what I''m going to write at this moment. My first thought was, ''I had an exhilarating experience. I can''t make a draft of it and then write it out. It''ll be better if I''m spontaneous.''\r\n\r\nHere I am.\r\n\r\nI looked at myself in the mirror. My eyes resembled those of Lord Voldemort - scarlet red. Yes, they were tired and looked bloodshot after the period of time I spent trying to figure out the character and personality of my story''s protagonist. It had been a good number of two hours and till now I just knew that my protagonist was a 15 year old girl who had cancer and then my thoughts trailed off into a fading train of words as my eyes flitted to the half written page.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://dkzstslcvgwbc.cloudfront.net/sites/default/files/resize/inline_image/images12_0-367x275.jpg" alt="" />\r\n\r\nMy inspiration looked as bleak as a candle flame that was dying out. I had tobring it back before it went extinct. With full determination, I picked up my pen, refraining myself from looking at the time, for time meant nothing for me right now. I had a story to write.\r\n\r\nI happily toiled away and burnt the midnight oil. Occasionally, there was a violent outbreak in my mind when a chunk of ideas used to aggressively knock on the doors of my brain, trying to get in. With great difficulty, I turned a deaf ear to them, for I knew that ''too many cooks spoil a good broth.'' The most painful and crucial part was the game changer, the twist in the story. It''s never easy to decide how you want your story to go about, specially when you''re not sure of what''s going to happen next and also when you don''t know what kind of literature people like reading. There are so many different tastes and preferences but just one story.\r\n\r\n''Pen down the first scenario that comes to the mind'' - that was the easiest strategy I planned to adopt. I am no pro at writing but only an emerging writer. I had to give this piece a lovely form with the simplest ideas. I had to give my characters the closure they needed. My characters were like my children, my own family and I couldn''t abandon them on some random page of a diary!\r\n\r\n<img src="https://dkzstslcvgwbc.cloudfront.net/sites/default/files/resize/inline_image/family_1-347x257.jpg" alt="" />\r\n\r\nIn sometime I realized my growing attachment to my newly found family that I had discovered in the hidden corners of my own mind. I found myself laughing, crying and rejoicing with them; protecting them from every destructive and masochistic thought that came to my mind. They were a part of me and hurting them would be like hurting myself.\r\n\r\nI was halfway through my story by then and I felt that this was one hell of a journey I had while writing one. Like a trip to a world from where I didn''t want to come back. I was free; to feel, do and say whatever I wanted to. It was beautiful and liberating with the right people. My creations were no less than people.\r\n\r\nHowever, this did include a big deal of mental dilemma, literary complications and ups and downs. Writing something is not a piece of cake, I assure you. You have to pick the right words. You can''t write something and turn it into something else. You have to know what you want and how you intend to go about it. You can''t lose track and then come back to write any nonsense just to make it a part of the work. It should make some sense.\r\n\r\n<img src="https://dkzstslcvgwbc.cloudfront.net/sites/default/files/resize/inline_image/hotguy-443x295.jpg" alt="" />\r\n\r\nWell, enough said, I snapped back to reality as I realized that the story was now nearing the climax. That''s what broke my heart. This had to end anyway. Sooner or later. They were going away from me. Yet another family was going to be preserved in the pages of my diary. Another lesson and wonderful experience with memories to cherish. Like a part of myself had latched onto those people I talked to but never seen. The pain ripped me apart. Into a million pieces.\r\n\r\nMaybe what Stephen King said was right after all.\r\n\r\n"JK Rowling created seven <em>Horcruxes</em>. She put a part of her soul in every book and now her books will live forever"\r\n\r\nI guess I did the same. But it was painful enough with just one story.\r\n\r\nThe essence of a story is different when it''s complete. It''s captivating. I could go on reading mine for hours and hours but not get bored. To make myself believe that the pain would subside and lie to my heart that it wasn''t over.\r\n\r\nA completed story is a wonder to behold.\r\n\r\n<strong>A beautiful heartbreak.</strong>', 'The beautiful heartbreak', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-beautiful-heartbreak', '', '', '2015-06-10 20:21:39', '2015-06-10 14:51:39', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=229', 0, 'post', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(223, 1, '2015-06-06 23:04:11', '2015-06-06 17:34:11', '&nbsp;\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Isn''t it a funny thing? </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">What you think you see are words </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">But rather images aligning </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">With perfect lines and curves </span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Why are birth and death called so? </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Why is a cow''s moo; a moo?</span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">The shirt you wear, your mother''s hair </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">A baby''s eyes and the sky; both a calming blue. </span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">We can''t live without these little puzzles</span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">When linked, they provide clues </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">To thoughts, to life and to victorious endeavours </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">To literature, conversation, song... they''re yours to choose</span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Words contain questions and answers </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">They last thoughout the ages </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">My grandfather''s favourite fairytale </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Or the science gathered among the pages </span></p>\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">And these words bring people together </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">Language unites and sets us free </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">But it is same words that bind us </span></p>\r\n<p dir="ltr" style="line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;"><span style="font-size: 51px; font-family: Arial; color: #000000; vertical-align: baseline; background-color: transparent;">As when two different cultures meet. </span></p>\r\n&nbsp;', 'The Story of Words', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '222-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-06 23:04:11', '2015-06-06 17:34:11', '', 222, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/222-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(236, 2, '2015-06-20 19:36:14', '2015-06-20 14:06:14', 'A teacher asked one of her kindergarten students what he thought was his greatest milestone in life yet. Simply out of curiosity. The child answered, “What is a m..mile..milestone?” The teacher smiled and explained, “A milestone is an important event in someone’s life. Like when you turn ten years old or when you go to college!” The child thought for a minute and said, “My dad got me my first basketball yesterday. I think that was an important event in my life.”\r\n\r\nA son asked his father, what to him was his life’s most cherished milestone. “There are many”, the father said, “but the day I married your mother has been my most favourite ever since.”\r\n\r\nA friend asked her 38-year old, National Award winning Kathak teacher, what her single most important milestone in life was. She said, “I beat Cancer. Twice.”\r\n\r\nMy sister told me a few days ago that I must go out for drinks with her whenever I would visit her next. I asked her if she would be willing to look out for me if I went about hurling everywhere after. “Yes!”, she said. “Those are milestones too.”\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images1111.jpg"><img class=" size-full wp-image-241 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images1111.jpg" alt="images111" width="276" height="183" /></a>\r\n\r\nEach of us, no matter how old we are or where we come from, has a list of things that we might have achieved or are hopeful about achieving. When we strike out some things off that list, we call them milestones- things that remind us how far we have come, the things we witnessed on the way, the sacrifices we made to get where we are, and all that lies ahead.\r\n\r\nOne year is a long time. 365 days, 8,760 hours, 52,56,000 minutes and 3,15,36,000 seconds. Every moment is a new memory made. Every breath, every step, every sigh, every thought, every blink of the eye, every sight- is unique in its own way. When we put these elements in a string together, the multidimensional image of our one by gone year emerges.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-6.jpg"><img class=" size-full wp-image-239 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-6.jpg" alt="images (6)" width="275" height="183" /></a>\r\n\r\nOne year since you found your soul mate, one year since you got that car you had been saving all your life for, one year since you took that trip with your best friends, one year since your brother started attending school, one year since your dog passed away after having lived a long and healthy life, one year since your twins turned one, one year since that house got burned down, one year since you moved to a new continent, one year since you made a million new memories, since you shed a few tears, since you laughed so hard you could feel the pressure in your head- one year since you lived.\r\n\r\nThe past year has been special to the team of The Book Hub too. I asked the Owner-Developer to tell me how it all started. He said, “<em>Main bore ho raha tha. Mere paas bohot saari e-books padi thien. Sabko ek jagah upload kiya aur chaar pages ki website bana daali!</em>” (When I started out, I only did it to avoid getting bored. I had a lot of e-books, so I uploaded them at one place and created a four-page long website.) I was amazed, and to be honest, slightly disappointed. I was looking for something more solid, deep and meaningful behind the making of this website. And all I was given was “<em>boriyat</em>” (boredom). This was exactly when it struck me that we keep waiting for good things to shape up amidst much pomp and show while forgetting to realise that “life is what happens to us when we are busy making plans”, that life’s most magnificent pleasures are hidden away in the simplest folds of its fabric.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-7.jpg"><img class=" size-full wp-image-238 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/images-7.jpg" alt="images (7)" width="267" height="189" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe Book Hub began with a handful of college-going kids, brought together by the shared passion for books and a deep-seated interest in technology. And here we are- 365 days, 15,000 visitors (and counting) and with an outreach to over 20 countries later- celebrating our first milestone; growing slowly, yet steadily. So imperative and valuable are these events- those that have kept so many of us going; that gave us a reason to start afresh, to keep trying our hands at what we want to do, to bridge the gap between where we are and where we want to be, to believe in the miracle that is human life.\r\n\r\nI am reminded of something Shri Shri Ranbir Kapoorji said in one of his motion pictures that aids my purpose here, “<em>Kahin par pohonchane ke liye, kahin se nikalna bohot zaroori hota hai!</em>” (In order to get somewhere, it is necessary that we get away from somewhere!). Rightfully so. How do we plan on achieving another milestone otherwise, right?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2.jpg"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-237 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/2-300x206.jpg" alt="2" width="300" height="206" /></a>\r\n<p style="text-align: center">Well, we turned one today and it is almost surreal. We feel ‘one’derful!</p>', 'The Journey To The Milestone', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'the-journey-to-the-milestone', '', '', '2015-06-21 12:29:20', '2015-06-21 06:59:20', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=236', 0, 'post', '', 10);
