INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(102, 1, '2015-04-11 19:19:03', '2015-04-11 13:49:03', 'In the ‘Harry Potter’ series, how much do we actually focus on the one crucial character who had almost escaped having Harry’s fate just because he was born one day earlier than Harry? Who handled Snape’s wrath because if Lord Voldemort had gone for him, Lily would’ve survived? Who had his parents tortured to insanity by Bellatrix Lestrange and the damage was so strong his mother didn’t recognize him and he lived in burning hell everyday knowing that he would never have the same connection with them that he had before? We may not accept it but living a life knowing your parents don’t know you is a fate worse than being dead. Sorry Harry but at least you know your parents would know you if they were alive. Neville Longbottom has our sympathy here *I don’t mean to be rude people* Let’s give it up to Neville’s true Gryffindor personality!\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville1.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville1-300x155.jpg" alt="hp-neville" width="300" height="155" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-92" /></a>\r\n\r\nNevilleLongbottom is that one important character who literally determines the whole course of series. He could’ve easily been ‘The Chosen One’, allowing Harry to be a normal wizard boy on ‘The Hogwarts Express’ without a scar, sitting with other kids, laughing without worries. But destiny had different plans for him. He did land up with scars, psychological ones, a little more painful than Harry’s. He has quite a lot of followers and fans in the fandom and who can blame him?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/download.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/download.jpg" alt="download" width="194" height="260" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-84" /></a>\r\n\r\nNot to forget his excruciatingly painful and good looks, he’s got the soul and qualities of a true Gryffindor – humility, nobility, kindness, loyalty, fierce supportiveness and bravery. Neville is a crystal clear reflection of the ‘real-life- Gryffindors, who have a potential to be true heroes under the most dangerous and life threatening situations, but not be a ‘Superman’ while sleeping and waking up. He clearly understands that being a person isn’t about being ‘the one’ who is always noticed no matter where they go and thrashing up villains at every freaking chance they get (No offence Harry, but Neville has his own points and you know it), it’s about deciding your battles and know what’s close enough to your heart and worth fighting for. \r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville3.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville3-300x168.jpg" alt="hp-neville3" width="300" height="168" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-85" /></a>\r\n\r\nNeville could’ve easily gotten Harry’s life by a span of one SINGLE DAY, has Voldemort seen him as a ‘real threat’ and let Harry live a little more normally.\r\nNow if we try to clearly dig into a little research, J K. Rowling has actually drawn Neville’s character from someone parallel in the previous generation: The Marauders. She did this with a lot of thinking, taking into account other characters. Neville is (please don’t kill ME) Peter Pettigrew. Okay! I’ll take the hurl of swear words till your actually understand why this was observed. He is the one who usually tags along with the trio but is looked down upon by everyone as he’s not remarkably talented or suave. He’s like the priest who knows every one of Harry’s most important secrets and could easily spill the beans. But then AGAIN! He’s a truly loyal Gryffindor! In addition, Professor McGonagall calls Peter Pettigrew ‘foolish boy’. Just like him Neville is another pureblood who has technically no respect from the notable wizarding families. Neville is the kid everyone picks on when Harry, Ron and Hermione aren’t around to defend him; gullible and the easy mark. He could’ve been Peter’s brand new analog in the story. \r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-peter.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-peter-300x164.jpg" alt="hp-peter" width="300" height="164" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-86" /></a>\r\n\r\nReason being – he can either ruin a dish or make it the epitome of perfection. He’s the game changer, tide turner and the shiny hinge. (whatever you want to call him) Apart from this, he’s in the same position as Wormtail, who made all the hard choices Wormtail didn’t. Of all the characters, Neville is the only one who goes the furthest to prove that an individual’s destiny is in his hands.  He of course, possesses other characteristics worth talking about, other than his own. What is important here is how his strengths fill in group dynamics needed by the Marauders. He’s wanted by the trio the same way Lily, James and the Order of Phoenix wanted Peter. Just that Neville is more than upto the task.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville2.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville2-300x161.jpg" alt="hp-neville2" width="300" height="161" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-87" /></a> \r\n\r\nNeville teaches us a lesson in self-worth and shows us that having a strong personality doesn''t always mean that  you''re meant to lead people and will only make the right decisions. Society at large only sees the leaders and their closest friends are dismissed at the first glance, pretty much like Neville was dismissed by his classmates in the first year. However, he doesn’t let his peers’ attitude affect him enough to give up. Instead, over the years. His self-depreciation turns into persistent desire to improve and increase his skill set on offering help irrespective of its need and he figures out how he can best come of use in a fight.\r\nHis very first act of heroism is seen in ‘Harry Potter and the Philosopher’s Stone’ when he stands up to Harry, Ron and Hermione, becoming a victim to Hermione’s full ‘Body Bind’ curse which gives him enough points for Gryffindor to win the house Cup. He personally makes sure to announce Neville’s name at the last so as to make Neville proud of his bravery to stand up against his friends when he was right. (given that Dumbledore was actually scared that history would repeat itself and he was more than relieved that Neville chose a different road) Immediately after that incident, he avoids falling into Peter’s shoes by stepping away a little from the trio so that it showed people that his meekness isn’t a signal for people to mess around with him.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-3.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-3.jpg" alt="images (3)" width="276" height="183" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-94" /></a>\r\n\r\nHe’s the defender, the keeper of hope and a true friend. When Harry publicly claims to see Lord Voldemort in the fourth year, the world speculates and calls him a liar, making a mockery out of him. Neville however, sticks to his side and believes him, fighting with him unlike most who run away and pee in their pants when real danger comes. He keeps the alive the ‘Dumbledore’s Army’ in Hogwarts despite Harry’s absence. He assumes the leader’s role, which was the hardest job anyone could do given Snape was the Headmaster during that time and builds a refuge in the ‘Room of Requirement’. Despite witnessing the murders, tortures and kidnappings of his closest friends, he stays hopeful in the castle, hopefully waiting for Harry, Ron and Hermione to return. He’s the PRIME FACTOR for the ‘Battle of Hogwarts’ to take place. We can’t deny he was the spark that set the castle on fire. \r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville5.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/hp-neville5-300x159.jpg" alt="hp-neville5" width="300" height="159" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-89" /></a>\r\n\r\nLeaving all this aside, Neville doesn’t fail his parents as the perfect son. Neville’s bravery, strength and love for his family keeps him fighting on for them even though they’re no longer there. He makes it his goal to be that ideal son though his parents would never know of his feats, deeds and mark in the wizarding world. \r\nIn the final hour, fate is about to make history repeat itself when he’s given the same cowardly choice of joining Voldemort and taking the easy way out. He changes the game at that very moment by drawing the sword of Gryffindor out of the burning Sorting Hat and slicing off Nagini’s head, ending Voldemort’s life. This moment proves that Harry needs Neville just the way he needs Ron and Hermione to end the war and put a cork in the bottle. It all comes down to Neville – the boy who demanded respect from his friends at the very start no matter how he felt and he chose to do what was right because it was the hardest thing to do.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/downloadii.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/downloadii.jpg" alt="downloadii" width="271" height="186" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-93" /></a>\r\n\r\nNow that we actually observe Neville under a whole new light, we discover that he’s indeed, the truest of Gryffindors and balances the entire HP narrative. Which makes us think – what would’ve Peter Pettigrew been like if he had known that courage wasn’t about following blindly following someone but about choosing to do what was right even when nobody asked that of you. He taught us that in this huge world filled with people who blend in easily with the crowd  and are followed because they’re known, there are some people who may seem different and ‘out of place’ but sometimes, THEY are the ones who lead the world to a better future……\r\nHere are 3 whole pages, OUR tribute to the truest Gryffindor – Neville Longbottom ‘The Boy who Could’ve Been’ and ‘The Boy who Made History’\r\n#SaluteToNevilleLongbottom !\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-4.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/images-4.jpg" alt="images (4)" width="184" height="273" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-95" /></a>\r\n', 'The Game changer and truest Gryffindor', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '91-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-04-11 19:19:03', '2015-04-11 13:49:03', '', 91, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/91-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(60, 1, '2015-04-03 22:52:36', '2015-04-03 17:22:36', 'There’s no easy way to start on a specific point about books. A good book is the ultimate muse for a reader.\r\n\r\nSuch is their magic. Those stacks of pages filled with stories, experiences and tales in attractive covers are like gateways to a beautiful world of imagination where anyone can be what they want without being judged, mocked or instructed. An alternate universe into which eager readers slip to find themselves in the exotic worlds of their abstract minds.\r\n\r\nIt all starts with turning the first page of that treasure trove of indelible expressions: narration and connection which holds the reader close and engages the mind into an unforgettable literary adventure. The feel of a new book, smell of fresh pages, color of a new front cover and sight of the title to a reader is like a flower to a honeybee. Words wait to cast their spell on people. The ultimate fantasy of any reader is to either own an unbelievably big library at some point in their lives or sit in one corner of anywhere with a beverage, munchies and a good book.\r\n\r\nBooks have come a long way from illustrations, journals, autobiographies, testimonies, novels and who knows where this might all go. Reading is like a therapy and a good book is a vacation you need if you really want a break without troubling your pockets. Bonus points of reading – good reading habits, richer vocabulary with a better understanding of the language,  healthy mind exercise, getting a better chance to understand what the readers want and more knowledge.\r\n\r\nQuoting the iconic J.K. Rowling, “I don’t believe in magic. But words are, in my not-so-humble opinion, our most inexhaustible source of magic.” We really can’t argue with that now, can we?\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/book-2.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/book-2.jpg" alt="book 2" width="290" height="174" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-69" /></a>\r\n\r\nWe also know authors and writers who have spun magic with their words over the decades. To name a few renowned literary legends, there’s Jeffrey Archer, Dan Brown,  J. K. Rowling ( again), Ruskin Bond, Ayn Rand and Daniel Defoe.  Now let’s talk about the most common mistake we often make as readers – confusing writers with authors. Authors are the ones who create and invent plots and are the originators of ideas. Writers are the ones focusing on one idea and modifying it to suit their storyline. It’s more like a sub-class of the main class.\r\nTo add to it, books are like best friends – they never leave you no matter what. Reading a book is like preparing yourself to be strapped to a roller-coaster of emotions. It’s like reading an untold life story, discovering an exotic land, unraveling a mystery, knowing an unshared experience. It’s not always easy to pick up a book, but once you do it, it’s pretty much worth it. Also, reading books may have one of these outcomes (maybe even multiple):\r\n•	Sometimes, the story leaves such an impression on your life, your mind just hangs in there and ponders over what you just read. Great stories rarely come by and when that happens, it’ll be days before the reader’s mind is fresh enough to go on another literary adventure.\r\n•	Chances are the writer has taken a good idea and not done such a good job elaborating on it (Let’s face it! Everyone’s not good with ideas and expression). However, one bad book can help potential writers understand the Do’s and Don’ts of producing some real good reading material.\r\n•	At times, the engaging factors for the reader are the characters, their personalities and the way they handle the world. Intimate connection with characters is a common occurrence and this may result in them playing a big role to mould the reader into a person. So, yeah you could say the readers are in a big way affected by what kind of stories they read.\r\n•	This clause may be fatal if one is a hard-core reader (chuckles softly): Some books often have characters and storylines that are somehow deeply connected with how the real world is. The reader develops a strong affection for the characters and more than often sees them as a second family. They can relate to the fictional individuals and try to understand the situation they are in. This way, the story becomes an integral part of the reader’s life, giving him/her life lessons, countless memories and in some cases, a childhood. \r\n•	Books also have a big role in determining how the reader might end up looking at the world and behave accordingly. This you could say, is something like ‘temporary inspiration’. The plot could be so overpowering that for some time the reader could actually try and imitate the fictional individuals expecting the same outcome as in the book. Books, as we don’t usually expect, have a technical aspect too. They’re more than just words and language; intricately linked with our lives and understanding of what’s happening around us.\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books.jpg" alt="books" width="274" height="184" class="alignnone size-full wp-image-61" /></a>\r\n\r\nThe best part about them is – they don’t manipulate you. It’s a free world where you can venture off wherever your heart and mind lead you. A world which you can carry along with you everywhere. ‘Books are knowledge’ isn’t a fashion statement. It’s pretty much valid because some of them are authored or written by people who actually cement their storyline with some research to blend in fiction and reality. It’s like taking the reader on an imaginary tour yet keeping him within the real world. We can’t even say it’s not true.\r\n\r\nAlso, books are a more intimate form of expression since time immemorial. Over here, I’m actually talking about the hard-copies. There’s a strange love that only a true book-lover can understand when one gets to touch the book in all its dimensions. Technology and e-books can never replace real books that way. Tactility is something that helps the reader build a connection with what he’s about to read, according to psychological studies, it stimulates his curiosity as humans respond and react mostly to touch. \r\n\r\nBooks also have a crucial role in forming a person’s mindset. For instance: a person indulging way too often in fiction may end up being way too imaginative and mentally immature. Romance novels often make the reader develop the notion that love is a beautiful feeling (which it is, no doubt) but they may also cause the reader that love stories have a perfectly happy ending as usually portrayed in books. It could cause the person to mistake ‘like’ for ‘love’ and fall in love with the ‘concept of love’. It is amazing no doubt but one should always balance out the proportion in which he/she reads every genre, that’s the moral. (All said from personal experience)\r\n\r\nAlso, most importantly, books are an invaluable medium of communication. Talking and reaching out to people, sending across your views, opinions, stories and ideas with feedback in the form of critic’s review and the readership.  Apart from this, when people read, it surely raises some questions, which makes them interact with others who have read the same book. Interaction leads to bonding and it goes on.\r\n\r\nLooking at all this, we could reiterate the fact that books have more than just one aspect; social, personal, psychological and technical. An in-depth understanding of everything above would help us realize exactly how important are books in our lives. \r\nFor these very reasons, books are invaluable treasures for mankind that not only need to be preserved but also promoted, loved and respected. They are beautiful gifts that deserve to be cherished, beating hearts of book-lovers.\r\n\r\nIn conclusion, I would end with a well known saying,\r\n“They say humans only live one life, but a reader has already lived a billion.”<strong></strong> <a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books-1.jpg"><img src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/04/books-1-300x200.jpg" alt="books 1" width="300" height="200" class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-64" /></a>\r\n', 'More than just ''Books''', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'more-than-just-books', '', '', '2015-04-03 23:04:20', '2015-04-03 17:34:20', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=60', 0, 'post', '', 0);
