INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(233, 7, '2015-06-13 19:56:04', '2015-06-13 14:26:04', '<img class=" aligncenter" src="http://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/6/6b/DaVinciCode.jpg" alt="" width="320" height="479" />\r\n\r\nDan Brown in all his books emphasizes that all information, artworks and facts stated in his books are true. While for many years, I blindly believed this statement, recently I decided to do a background check at the legitimacy of this statement. Although initially everything seemed well in place, I slowly started stumbling upon factual errors and wrong information being sold to the public. Taking for granted that a majority of the readers will not know much about the backgrounds of the works, Dan Brown added mysterious societies and strange rituals which appealed to the audience, even more so because the audience mostly if not wholly believed that the these societies and rituals existed. I however felt a little cheated for being made to believe something that is not true and hence I would like to bring out a few factual errors in what is considered Dan Brown’s best work, The Da Vinci Code.\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong><em>The Priory of Sion:</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nAccording to the book, the Priory of Sion is an ancient organization connected to Goddess worship. Dan Brown writes that the organization was founded in 1099 and it was named after the Biblical Mount Zion. The truth is however very different. The Priory of Sion was actually founded in1956 by Pierre Plantard, Andre Bonhomme and others and was named after a mountain in France.\r\n<ol start="2">\r\n	<li><strong><em>Opus Dei</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe book claims that the Opus Dei is a monastic order which is the Pope’s ‘personal prelature’. Silas the murderer is said to be an Opus Dei monk who uses a cilice to flagellate himself and receives very deep wounds. Factually Opus Dei has no monks and Dan Brown greatly exaggerates the effects of voluntary mortification of flesh as the kind of wounds described in the book cannot be caused from a normal cilice.\r\n<ol start="3">\r\n	<li><strong><em>The Rosslyn Chapel</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe Chapel is a major feature in the last part of the novel, though many incorrect assertions were made about the structure. The book states that the Chapel was built by the Knights Templar, and contains a six-pointed Star of David worn into the stone floor although such star has never been seen in the floor. Also the chapel was founded by William Sinclair, 1st Earl of Caithness of the Scoto-Norman Sinclair family and not by the Knights Templar\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone" src="https://encrypted-tbn0.gstatic.com/images?q=tbn:ANd9GcR6KbQasx634TE8fmh9Y0XugyTcl0LNAVPcupet5a7eq9-8aM0U" alt="" width="259" height="194" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ol start="4">\r\n	<li><strong><em>The Vatican</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nIn the story, the Vatican is said to be the center of power in the early Catholic Church. It is said that that there is a reference to the Vatican in the Gnostic Writings of the 4<sup>th</sup> century. However it was not until the 15<sup>th</sup> century that there was anything like official power in the vicinity of the Vatican Hill in Rome. In the 4<sup>th</sup> century all that existed of the Vatican was a little more than a church and cemetery by the side of the road. Also the book claims that St. Peter’s is a cathedral, although Saint Peter’s is more of a church technically.\r\n<ol start="5">\r\n	<li><strong><em>Geography</em></strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThe book’s storyline that the “Albino Monk” was arrested in France, imprisoned in Andorra and escaped to Spain, demonstrates the lack of basic research that would be gleaned from a quick glance at a map or tourist guide. It is improbable that someone arrested along the French coast would be imprisoned in another country (in this case Andorra which is a different jurisdiction and several hundred kilometers away up in the Pyrenean Mountains). After the scene in the Temple Church, London, the heroes of the story take the tube from Temple Station to King’s College. In fact King’s College is nearer to the Temple Church than to Temple Station, and any tube journey would have carried them further away from King’s College. Brown also states “The chapel’s geographic coordinates fall precisely on the north-south meridian that runs through Glastonbury”. This statement is incorrect: Rosslyn Chapel lies more towards the east-west meridian. Brown appears to have confused geographic north with magnetic north.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone" src="http://i.infopls.com/images/Europemap-2010.gif" alt="" width="713" height="535" />\r\n\r\nIt is not just the The Da Vinci Code. All of Dan Brown’s works have major factual fallacies, which have been introduced to take advantage of the fact that any mysterious object gains much more interest if it is rendered to be factually correct. As far as the story is concerned, the suspense, the thrill, the build-up, everything is very well put and the book has all the ingredients to make an interesting read, however keeping the factual inaccuracies in mind, my outlook of the book has changed from “A must read book, filled with well researched information which provides an insight into history along with an interesting storyline” to “Just another historical fiction thriller”.', 'The Da Vinci Code: Of Facts or Fallacies?', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '232-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-13 19:56:04', '2015-06-13 14:26:04', '', 232, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/232-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
