INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(251, 1, '2015-06-24 19:44:20', '2015-06-24 14:14:20', '"Hero or Villain?" is a frequent question that acts as conversation starter in social circles and people usually prefer the villain. It is a bit surprising, to say the least, that people would deliberately choose a character that is portrayed as vindictive, resentful and even criminal over someone who is amiable and righteous.\r\n\r\n...\r\n\r\nA memorable tale is always determined by its plot and more importantly, its characters. A thrilling chemistry between the antagonist and protagonist that leaves the audience at the edge of their seats is sure to be a blockbuster or a bestseller. But the best stories that are a class apart are those with a well-defined villain.\r\nSure, ultimately the hero saves the day but it''s the villain that steals the show. Here are a few reasons why the hated are really the most loved.\r\n\r\n1. There would be no story without a villain.\r\n\r\nOne can only appreciate the light once you see the darkness. A hero''s ''pristine nature'' can be shown if has a plan to foil and an anti-hero to defeat. They are rivals yet complementary to each other and a perfect plot.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://i.ytimg.com/vi/0_mEDo0D7f4/hqdefault.jpg" alt="" width="311" height="233" />\r\n\r\n2. An engrossing back story.\r\n\r\nBehind their devilish schemes, heinous intentions and hardened personalities, lie a hundred secrets why villains turned into monsters.\r\n\r\nTake for example, Bill the Butcher (or William Cutting), the antagonist in Gangs of New York. Inspired by real life gangster William Poole, Bill was a violent man hell-bent on revenge against immigrants who were responsible for his father''s death. He was known for his moral code, his patriotism and sense of honour. Today he is famously remembered for his last words, "Thank God... I died a true American."\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://www.monologuedb.com/wp-content/uploads/2011/03/daniel-day-lewis-bill-the-butcher-cutting-gangs-of-new-york.jpg" alt="" width="462" height="308" />\r\n\r\nHeathcliff (Wuthering Heights), an iconic villain in English literature is a character still yet to be fully understood even after a century of his existence. Born as a homeless orphan but sheltered and mentored by Mr. Earnshaw, Heathcliff, Heathcliff falls in love with Catherine Earnshaw who betrays their love and marries Edgar Linton, a man of better social and economic background. In a rage of vengeance and sadness, Heathcliff becomes a living nightmare in a gentleman''s disguise.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://36.media.tumblr.com/tumblr_lnnalzPlNN1qe5f96o1_1280.jpg" alt="" width="411" height="274" />\r\n\r\n3. Honestly, they''re smarter.\r\n\r\nThere''s nothing more appealing than cunning intellect and a cunning intellect is a villain''s forte.\r\n\r\nLight Yagami (Death Note) could control death and the supernatural.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://static.comicvine.com/uploads/scale_super/1/11495/240324-73255-light-yagami.jpg" alt="" width="400" height="225" />\r\n\r\nMister Sinister (X-Men), a scientific genius could alter his human genome to be invulnerable and ageless. Also he resuscitated Apocalypse, carrier of the first mutant X-gene. That''s pretty damn smart.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://static.comicvine.com/uploads/original/11113/111133725/3864874-1.jpg" alt="" width="225" height="301" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nMrs. Eleanor Iselin (The Manchurian Candidate) is a ruthless Communist agent who plans to take over America. Her cold blooded and domineering attitude towards even her husband and son and her ambition to succeed makes her one of the smartest villains of all time.\r\n\r\n<strong><img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://www.morethings.com/fan/manchurian_candidate/plot-revealed-angela_lansbury-laurence_harvey09.jpg" alt="" width="440" height="222" /></strong>\r\n\r\n4. People are attracted to imperfections.\r\n\r\nEveryone wants to be perfect but we''re not. Heroes on paper and screens are the closest depiction to perfection. They represent goodwill, selflessness and struggle. They represent silver linings.\r\n\r\nVillains are a realistic portrayal of mankind''s flaws, exaggerations of man''s sins. They are greedy (Shylock), ambitious (Macbeth), broken (Voldemort), vengeful (Maleficent) and desirable (Jennifer in Jennifer''s Body). There is raw, crass and unabashed emotion in a villain which makes a story all the more better. In the real world, there is no black and white but shades of grey.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class="" src="http://img4.wikia.nocookie.net/__cb20120727155045/disney/images/5/5e/Puzzle-clementoni-disney-villains-panorama-1000-p-CLM39088.5-0.jpg" alt="" width="756" height="272" />\r\n\r\n5. We cling to the hope that they might change sides.\r\n\r\nContinuing from the previous point, we truly want to believe that a villain has a human heart and even though tortured can seek redemption,\r\n\r\nDr. Gru from the Despicable Me series is a classic example. From conniving to steal the moon to become a doting father of three is a complete and delightful change of character.\r\n\r\nMaybe Claude Frollo (The Hunchback of Notre Dame) could find it in his otherwise compassionate heart to give way to reason (for he was a knowledgeable man) and let go of his unrequited love for Esmeralda.\r\n\r\nMaybe Loki (Marvel Universe) accepts his fate as an adopted brother and rather helps Thor in the safekeeping of Asgard.\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class=" aligncenter" src="http://www.despicablemegames.info/games/images/18-despicable-me-2-animation-movie.jpg" alt="" width="557" height="348" />\r\n\r\nThis is where our imagination and expectations go wild, fellow readers.\r\n\r\n6. Psychos are entertaining. :)\r\n\r\nThere are some villains who capture our hearts but there are some who are simply blood-curdling and we love every second of it.\r\n\r\nChristoph Waltz as SS Colonel Hans Landa (Inglorious Basterds) was horrifying and brilliant.\r\n\r\nAmerican Psycho is now generated as academic work because of Christian Bale''s smooth transitions as a man of great reputation to a psychotic serial killer.\r\n\r\nAlso, how can one forget the loathsome woman in pink, Dolores Umbridge or Cruella De Vil.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<a href="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/tumblr_mgn2k8hSVW1r1mtsdo1_500.gif"><img class=" size-medium wp-image-250 aligncenter" src="http://blog.thebookhub.in/wp-content/uploads/2015/06/tumblr_mgn2k8hSVW1r1mtsdo1_500-300x181.gif" alt="tumblr_mgn2k8hSVW1r1mtsdo1_500" width="300" height="181" /></a>\r\n\r\n7. (Bonus reason) A good looking villain is like icing on a cake.\r\n\r\nWith the slyness of a fox and the looks of an angel, our hearts turn into a frenzy of hate and passion. We would gladly give into the dark side if they were the villain of our story. ;)\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\n<img id="irc_mi" class="" src="http://static.comicvine.com/uploads/original/11113/111136107/3993372-8788862310-dexte.jpg" alt="" width="302" height="227" /><img id="irc_mi" class=" alignright" src="http://vignette2.wikia.nocookie.net/marvelmovies/images/a/ae/Mystique_2000.jpg/revision/latest?cb=20130813004115" alt="" width="191" height="258" />', 'Behind the Facade of Villainy', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '247-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-06-24 19:44:20', '2015-06-24 14:14:20', '', 247, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/247-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(259, 7, '2015-07-04 19:18:15', '2015-07-04 13:48:15', 'Non-fiction technically means any form of writing or cinema which is not a figment of the authors’ imagination. It includes biographies and autobiographies, historical accounts and even textbooks. As a general observance (and I may be wrong here) I have seen that people who read, mostly read fiction, (at least the younger generation) and non-fiction is a little neglected. Non-fiction is considered boring and dull, and often not of interest to those who do not, in general have an interest towards say history or current affairs. The situation is such that many people do not even consider reading non-fiction because in their minds they have a preconceived notion that it will not appeal to them.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone" src="http://authorearnings.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/50000-unit-sales-by-category1.jpg" alt="" width="303" height="256" /></p>\r\nI began reading when I was in third or fourth grade and read only fiction till I was in tenth grade. It so happened that somewhere in tenth grade a friend suggested I should read the autobiography of Andre Agassi titled ‘Open’. Although initially I was totally against the idea, I decided to give it a try and the book opened for me a new world. The world of non-fiction. Coming back to the original question. Why should you read non-fiction (or at least give it a try)? Here’s why:\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class=" aligncenter" src="https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/236x/1b/b3/88/1bb38852971f5ecc08349fc31ad5244e.jpg" alt="" width="289" height="385" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>You come across many different subjects and real-world situations. Reading non-fiction gets you in touch with issues such as Satanism, life of drug dealers, youth culture and capitalism, youth racial relations, dynamics of bullying in middle school students, role of social media in the 2010 Egyptian uprisings, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>You’ll learn to value people as human-beings and not as superhuman emotional saviors. In most fiction novels, the hero of the plot often has superhuman like capabilities. Be it Robert Langdon, James Bond, Hercule Poirot, Nancy Drew or others. Be it stories of loyalty, bravery, romance or betrayal, the books often have many scenes which. In a real-world scenario would be impossible to replicate. Non-fiction on the other hand tells you exactly how things work.</li>\r\n	<li>Reading non-fiction gives practical, daily life-applicable knowledge that can be used to interact with others. For a discussion on fiction, all the parties taking part must have read the subject partly or wholly, but that is not the case with non-fiction. In case of non-fiction the subjects are such that everyone will have their opinions about the matter. Subjects like the Human Rights abuse in Guatanamo Bay can garner a more productive discussion than say the life of David Copperfield.</li>\r\n	<li>You can impart knowledge. Say you read S. Hussain Zaidi’s ‘Dongri to Dubai, Six Decades of the Mumbai Mafia’, you will have a lot of anecdotes and incidents about the lives of the dons of Mumbai to intrigue others with, or if you have read Rafael Nadal’s autobiography, ‘Rafa: My Story’, you will be able to tell tales of the determination and hard-work that made him on the best tennis players ever.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="https://tejasghetia.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/dongri-to-dubai.jpeg" alt="" width="204" height="318" />                 <img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="http://img5a.flixcart.com/image/book/7/3/3/rafa-my-story-400x400-imad9g9gx2abtppq.jpeg" alt="" width="200" height="313" />\r\n\r\nReading non-fiction comes with its own set of assets. Do not try to answer the question of whether you will like it or not without giving it a try. To help you start, I’ll also add a list of books you can begin with, apart from the ones I have already mentioned.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/5/57/NoEasyDayCoverArt.jpg" alt="" width="209" height="314" />                <img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51KP9Pb8HKL.jpg" alt="" width="192" height="294" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Unbroken: A World War II Story, Laura Hillenbrand</li>\r\n	<li>A Short History of Nearly Everything, Bill Bryson</li>\r\n	<li>Black Boy, Richard Wright</li>\r\n	<li>The Boys in the Boat: Nine Americans and Their Epic Quest for Gold in the 1936 Berlin Olympics, Daniel James Brown</li>\r\n	<li>Black Hawk Down, Mark Bowden</li>\r\n	<li>No Easy Day: The Firsthand Account of the Mission that Killed Osama bin Laden, Mark Owen and Kevin Maurer</li>\r\n	<li>From Byculla to Bangkok, S. Hussain Zaidi</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="http://d.gr-assets.com/books/1320520930l/6480781.jpg" alt="" width="211" height="312" />\r\n\r\nI hope I have been successful in implanting an idea of reading non-fiction in your minds. There is a world out there that will teach you a lot of different things, waiting to be explored. So go ahead and give non-fiction a try. My apologies if I have hurt any sentiments in my comparison of non-fiction and fiction.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Why You Should Read Non-fiction', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'why-you-should-read-non-fiction', '', '', '2015-07-04 19:20:43', '2015-07-04 13:50:43', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=259', 0, 'post', '', 0);
