INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(263, 7, '2015-07-04 19:20:43', '2015-07-04 13:50:43', 'Non-fiction technically means any form of writing or cinema which is not a figment of the authors’ imagination. It includes biographies and autobiographies, historical accounts and even textbooks. As a general observance (and I may be wrong here) I have seen that people who read, mostly read fiction, (at least the younger generation) and non-fiction is a little neglected. Non-fiction is considered boring and dull, and often not of interest to those who do not, in general have an interest towards say history or current affairs. The situation is such that many people do not even consider reading non-fiction because in their minds they have a preconceived notion that it will not appeal to them.\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class="alignnone" src="http://authorearnings.com/wp-content/uploads/2014/02/50000-unit-sales-by-category1.jpg" alt="" width="303" height="256" /></p>\r\nI began reading when I was in third or fourth grade and read only fiction till I was in tenth grade. It so happened that somewhere in tenth grade a friend suggested I should read the autobiography of Andre Agassi titled ‘Open’. Although initially I was totally against the idea, I decided to give it a try and the book opened for me a new world. The world of non-fiction. Coming back to the original question. Why should you read non-fiction (or at least give it a try)? Here’s why:\r\n<p style="text-align: center;"><img class=" aligncenter" src="https://s-media-cache-ak0.pinimg.com/236x/1b/b3/88/1bb38852971f5ecc08349fc31ad5244e.jpg" alt="" width="289" height="385" /></p>\r\n\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>You come across many different subjects and real-world situations. Reading non-fiction gets you in touch with issues such as Satanism, life of drug dealers, youth culture and capitalism, youth racial relations, dynamics of bullying in middle school students, role of social media in the 2010 Egyptian uprisings, etc.</li>\r\n	<li>You’ll learn to value people as human-beings and not as superhuman emotional saviors. In most fiction novels, the hero of the plot often has superhuman like capabilities. Be it Robert Langdon, James Bond, Hercule Poirot, Nancy Drew or others. Be it stories of loyalty, bravery, romance or betrayal, the books often have many scenes which. In a real-world scenario would be impossible to replicate. Non-fiction on the other hand tells you exactly how things work.</li>\r\n	<li>Reading non-fiction gives practical, daily life-applicable knowledge that can be used to interact with others. For a discussion on fiction, all the parties taking part must have read the subject partly or wholly, but that is not the case with non-fiction. In case of non-fiction the subjects are such that everyone will have their opinions about the matter. Subjects like the Human Rights abuse in Guatanamo Bay can garner a more productive discussion than say the life of David Copperfield.</li>\r\n	<li>You can impart knowledge. Say you read S. Hussain Zaidi’s ‘Dongri to Dubai, Six Decades of the Mumbai Mafia’, you will have a lot of anecdotes and incidents about the lives of the dons of Mumbai to intrigue others with, or if you have read Rafael Nadal’s autobiography, ‘Rafa: My Story’, you will be able to tell tales of the determination and hard-work that made him on the best tennis players ever.</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="https://tejasghetia.files.wordpress.com/2013/04/dongri-to-dubai.jpeg" alt="" width="204" height="318" />                 <img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="http://img5a.flixcart.com/image/book/7/3/3/rafa-my-story-400x400-imad9g9gx2abtppq.jpeg" alt="" width="200" height="313" />\r\n\r\nReading non-fiction comes with its own set of assets. Do not try to answer the question of whether you will like it or not without giving it a try. To help you start, I’ll also add a list of books you can begin with, apart from the ones I have already mentioned.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/5/57/NoEasyDayCoverArt.jpg" alt="" width="209" height="314" />                <img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="http://ecx.images-amazon.com/images/I/51KP9Pb8HKL.jpg" alt="" width="192" height="294" />\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li>Unbroken: A World War II Story, Laura Hillenbrand</li>\r\n	<li>A Short History of Nearly Everything, Bill Bryson</li>\r\n	<li>Black Boy, Richard Wright</li>\r\n	<li>The Boys in the Boat: Nine Americans and Their Epic Quest for Gold in the 1936 Berlin Olympics, Daniel James Brown</li>\r\n	<li>Black Hawk Down, Mark Bowden</li>\r\n	<li>No Easy Day: The Firsthand Account of the Mission that Killed Osama bin Laden, Mark Owen and Kevin Maurer</li>\r\n	<li>From Byculla to Bangkok, S. Hussain Zaidi</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<img class="alignnone aligncenter" src="http://d.gr-assets.com/books/1320520930l/6480781.jpg" alt="" width="211" height="312" />\r\n\r\nI hope I have been successful in implanting an idea of reading non-fiction in your minds. There is a world out there that will teach you a lot of different things, waiting to be explored. So go ahead and give non-fiction a try. My apologies if I have hurt any sentiments in my comparison of non-fiction and fiction.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;', 'Why You Should Read Non-fiction', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '259-revision-v1', '', '', '2015-07-04 19:20:43', '2015-07-04 13:50:43', '', 259, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/259-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES(265, 1, '2015-07-08 18:57:37', '2015-07-08 13:27:37', '"Abhay! Look Behind"\n\n"What? I can''t hear you Piya!"\n\n"Look behind at that.."\n\nI''ve been a regular at public speaking competitions, winning most of them. I pride myself on my speaking skills, the debates I win, the speeches I give, that enthrall crowds. And yet, that day, I could do nothing to prevent the words from dying in their wake. \n\nBeings of varied proportions; Some make one inclined to tearing their hair out while some of these beings make one gratuitous. And the best thing is that almost all the time, both of them are same person. The only kind of godsend capable of making one cry, laugh, smile and fume. They''re called brothers. \n\nMy brother, he was a mixture of all. My go-to person, my literary critic, listening with a patient ear to all my exploits, and when I had finally finished rambling, he would either pass a sarcastic comment or snide me, depending on the content of my stories. Being four years elder to me, he bossed me around like I was a toddler. He would hit me, tease me, and irritate me as much as he wanted to, but at the same time, couldn''t bear a single tear in my eye. May the lord be with the person who had caused it, for he wouldn''t hesitate to give that person a piece of his mind, even if that person happened to be our mother.\n\nComing to my mother. She''s a pretty, kind lady who makes the world more beautiful by her mere presence. When asked about her children, she always had the same answer, “Abhay and Piya! Sweethearts they are. They are the reason my eyes twinkle, my heart beats and my life seems worthwhile!” \n\nThere was however, just one slight anomaly to this otherwise perfect woman.   She was jealous of her children. My mother, rather, our mother was jealous of us, her Abhay and Piya, her sweethearts. She had always imagined that she would be her children’s best friend, the first person they would turn to, whether they wanted to crack a joke or share their troubles. But Abhay and me, we had each other. To us, the world didn’t seem worth living in if either of us didn’t exist. We had made an promised each other, in our own childish way, that we would always tell each other everything first, never let anyone or anything come in between us, and stay together, forever. Little did I know, that destiny would do whatever it could, just to prove us wrong.\n\nSince the day I was born, Abhay was used to taking care of me. He was fascinated by my little antics. Every sound that escaped my lips, every little shake of my limbs had to be applauded by him. Mom tells me, he used to speak to me for hours at a stretch, in his own toddler language, his enthusiasm never fleeting. His protective attitude bordered on extremes; he would not trust anyone, family or foe, even when it came to them taking me in their lap. And if they somehow forced me away from him, he would hover there, eyes like a hawk, watching their every action, like a guardian angel, ensuring my safety. \n\nHe took it upon himself to teach me how to speak. And being the dutiful sister I always was, the first word I said was not ‘dada’ (the Bengali word for brother), inviting a fresh round of fury to my mother''s emotions. It was with him that I used to crawl around the house. It was with his support that I took my first steps. It was he who I had eyes for at the park whereas every other child would be escorted by their father. It was because of him that I didn’t shed a single tear while going to school, because I always knew I’d find him there. It was he who had to be there beside me while I revised the alphabet, though it was mom who was teaching me. And it was him, at the end of the day, the person I needed near me while mom sang me to sleep. It was in his presence, even then, that I felt most safe and secure.\n\nAs we grew up, it was him I turned to for advice, be it about friends, studies or boys. He was the first person I used to tell about my fights with my friends. It was he whom I asked for help while stuck over a math problem. It was he who I confided in first about my first crush and consequently, my first heart break. Looking back, I cannot remember a single moment I didn’t feel his need. That doesn’t mean we didn’t fight. But it was always over the silliest things, like who would eat the last slice of pizza or who would switch off the light at night. \n\nI remember the way he used to behave when his friends were over. When we were little, I used to play with his friends all day long, and he didn’t have any problem. But, when I, in his words “blossomed from a bud into a beautiful flower”, he wouldn’t even let me be in the same room with him and his friends, let alone speak to them. He didn’t have a problem with me speaking to boys; it was just ‘his’ boys. He knew exactly how his friends were and he didn’t want me near them, at all. I was his sweet little sister, and he wanted me to stay that way.\n\nI always had someone to walk with, be it to tuitions, to my bus stop, to the nearby stationery shop or to the grocery shop across the road. There were two reasons for this- one, we loved walking together and second, living in Kolkata, it wasn’t safe for me to walk alone. And according to Abhay, there was a third reason as well- apparently; I didn’t know how to cross the road. Which, in a way, was true. It wasn’t like I didn’t know; it was just that I didn’t have the patience to wait for all the cars to go. And Abhay, being the over-protective brother he was, would obviously not let me go alone.\n\nMom and Dad would often leave us alone at home and go for their social parties. With Abhay around, they were not scared and they had no reason to be. That night also they did the same. They gave the home keys to Abhay and went. As per our routine, as soon as they stepped in the lift, music started blaring and we started practicing salsa. It was a well kept secret, for no one but I knew, that Abhay wanted to desperately learn salsa, but was too ashamed to admit it. I had taken matters in my own hands and being a good dancer, had started teaching him. We danced around the house for about an hour and fell on the sofa, exhausted.\n\nDinner that day was a quiet affair as both as we were engrossed in the television and too tired to speak. Suddenly, an advertisement about chocolate started playing. My taste buds started tingling. Coincidentally, the succeeding advertisement was about ice cream. I suddenly started craving ice cream. I started asking, demanding, pleading, nagging and even begging to Abhay to let me go out and eat ice cream and come. But unsurprisingly, he didn’t allow me. I put on my puppy dog face and emotionally blackmail him. I relentlessly kept on trying. Finally, he altered my conditions and came up with what at that time seemed a brilliant plan. He proposed that he’d go and get me my ice cream, while I stayed inside the house and he locked me from outside. Desperate to eat my ice cream, I readily agreed.\n\nHe did as he had suggested, locked me in and went. I went to the balcony and was watching him. So eager was I to eat my ice cream, I was urging him by shouting from my balcony to go fast. He was crossing the road at that time. Continuing to walk, he turned back to stick his tongue out at me and started knowingly walking slowly just to irritate me. I was about to shout at him again when what happened the next second changed my life. My scream died in my throat and my eyes widened with horror. So engrossed we were in our playful banter that none of us had noticed the busy street around him. We were, as usual, lost in our own world. By the time I saw the truck, it was too late…\n\nEverything that happened next is a blur. I saw a body, a large crimson stain and I started mumbling incoherently. The truck driver leapt out, his face an echo of the mask of horror I was wearing. There was however, a slight difference. In his eyes, there was fear; fear of what had happened and fear of what would happen. A large group of people crowded around the body, cutting off my view entirely. It was then that my voice came back to me. I started screaming, shouting at anyone and everyone who was present to help my brother, my Abhay, my angel. The people just stood there, unresponsive. They were simply staring, doing nothing to help. I didn’t want to go away from there, but I had no other option. I ran to the door and tried to open it. But it wouldn’t budge! I realized Abhay had locked me. I couldn’t go out!\n\nI ran back to the balcony, and endless stream of tears running down my face. I tried shouting again, to somehow get those lifeless and emotionless people to help, but they stayed still, just like statues. There was not even a flicker of life or recognition in their eyes. I gave up hope on them. I somehow controlled my tears and called an ambulance. Damn this country and the government and the cars and their owners, I thought, unable to resist but curse India, a nation where pizza comes before an ambulance does. I then called mom and dad up, and was just able to manage a ‘Come back home right now!’ before I broke down again. \n\nMom, being a mother, realized that something was wrong just by hearing my voice and rushed back home with dad. Those 10 minutes it took them to reach home were hell. Standing there, seeing my brother breathe his last before my own eyes, locked up in my only safe sanctuary, my house which now seemed like a prison and the railing like the bars, helpless. It is a feeling that cannot be described. It can just be felt. And those unlucky few who have felt it will agree, it is a feeling better not felt.\n\nFinally, finally my parents reached. And they brought with them the welcome sound of the ambulance siren, which otherwise I always thought to be ominous. My dad raced up, unlocked me and we ran back down. Mom stayed with Abhay, crying and screaming at the attendants to hurry and lift him up on the stretcher. The three of us climbed in, none of us speaking, our labored breaths the only sound apart from the beep of the monitors attached to Abhay. And then there was a change in the sound of the monitor which was measuring his heartbeat…..\n\nAbhay died that day. I lost my brother, my best friend, my world. There’s a hole in my chest that grows every minute. I unintentionally associate everything happening around me with him, making me feel like there are claws scratching on the edges of that hole. It feels like I’m living in a vacuum. There’s an emptiness around me, which no matter how many people I am with, doesn’t get filled. When you build your world around someone and that person no longer stays in it, everything comes crumbling down because there’s no one to hold it up. I lost everything that day. \n\nI lost my brother because I wanted to eat a stupid ice cream and didn’t have the common sense to not disturb him while he was crossing the road. I lost him because I’m the most selfish person in the world who had the best brother anyone could ever have. I lost him because I never deserved him. \n\nIt’s been almost a year since I lost Abhay, and myself, and there’s a wall around me that I can’t break. Life has ceased to have any meaning for me now. I eat, I sleep, I study, I cry and I breathe. But that’s all I do. I’m a walking zombie. My eyes no longer have any emotion in them. They are a true reflection of what I’m feeling inside. The pain washes over me every second I’m awake. \n\nI’m waiting for my mind to stop reacting, the tears to stop falling and my emotions to stop disillusioning me. I’m waiting for the day when I’ll be able to accept that Abhay actually has gone. I’m waiting for the time when I stop looking around for Abhay, and have him tell me it was all just a silly prank he was playing on me. I’m waiting for my ears to stop straining, trying to listen to his full-throated laugh again. I’m waiting for my heart beat to not increase whenever I see a tall guy with dark hair walk by. I’m waiting for the guilt to pass. I’m waiting for my mom to stop crying whenever she looks at me. I’m waiting for dad to crack a smile. My foolish, yearning heart overrules my mind and is and will always be waiting for Abhay to come back.\n\nWritten by Mahima Agarwala', 'Waiting', '', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'waiting', '', '', '2015-07-08 18:57:37', '2015-07-08 13:27:37', '', 0, 'http://blog.thebookhub.in/?p=265', 0, 'post', '', 0);
